         <h1>Eric Hebborn, Boastful Art Forger, Is Dead at 61 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Eric Hebborn , a self-proclaimed forger of Old Master paintings and drawings whose works found their way into some of the world 's great collections , died on Thursday at San Giacomo Hospital here . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 61 . <br><blue>3</blue>Mr. Hebborn collapsed in the Trastevere district , where he had lived much of the last 30 years . <br><blue>4</blue>The Italian authorities have ordered an autopsy to determine the cause of death . <br><blue>5</blue>In a memoir published in 1993 , Mr. Hebborn disclosed details of a lifelong career spent faking the works of Old Masters . <br><blue>6</blue>Hebborns bearing names like Bruegel , Piranesi , Van Dyck and Corot found homes , Mr. Hebborn wrote , in the Metropolitan Museum of Art , the British Museum and the Pierpont Morgan Library . <br><blue>7</blue>He said others remained , undetected , in private collections throughout the world . <br><blue>8</blue>To those who admired him , Mr. Hebborn was a talented if eccentric figure who did little harm . <br><blue>9</blue>Col. Roberto Conforti , the head of an Italian police unit that combats art theft , was quoted today as describing Mr. Hebborn 's paintings as often more beautiful than the originals . <br><blue>10</blue>" He once told me , " Colonel Conforti said , " ' Others paint nature . <br><blue>11</blue>I paint art . ' " <br><blue>12</blue>But critics , and there were many , accused him of hypocritically justifying his activity in his autobiography , " Drawn to Trouble : Confessions of a Master Forger " ( Random House ) , as a moral crusade to deflate the pretensions of the official art world , while at the same time reaping profit from works of forgery . <br><blue>13</blue>In 1994 , a former partner and lover , Graham Smith , sought to debunk him , contending that some of Mr. Hebborn 's proclaimed fakery was itself faked . <br><blue>14</blue>In remarks published in Art and Auction magazine , Mr. Smith contended , and the claim proved to be true , that Mr. Hebborn had not , as he had boasted , produced a Bruegel etching now in the Metropolitan Museum of Art . <br><blue>15</blue>Mr. Hebborn dismissed the challenge as " bad memory " on Mr. Smith 's part . <br><blue>16</blue>Mr. Hebborn was born in England in a working-class family . <br><blue>17</blue>As a youth , he won prizes at the Royal Academy in London , and later acquired useful skills the school did not teach by working as an art restorer . <br><blue>18</blue>" I began , little by little , to develop my abilities and improve my knowledge of the materials and methods of the Old Masters until I would one day be able to ' restore ' a whole painting , from nothing at all , " he wrote in his memoir . <br><blue>19</blue>Amiable and engaging , with bushy hair and a beard , he struck up friendships in high places , including one with Sir Anthony Blunt , surveyor of the Queen 's pictures , director of the Courtauld Institute of Art in London and a Soviet spy , from whom Mr. Hebborn said he learned much about the politics of art collecting . <br><blue>20</blue>Mr. Hebborn 's forging was unmasked by dealers in the late 1970 's , though he never faced criminal prosecution . <br><hr><br><blue>1(3)</blue>: <m_str>Col. Roberto Conforti , the head of an Italian police unit that combats art theft</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>me</m_str> (10_5) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>his memoir</m_str> (18_50) 	<m_str>a memoir published in 1993</m_str> (5_2) 	<br><blue>3(34)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Hebborn</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>my</m_str> (18_15) 	<m_str>Mr. Hebborn</m_str> (14_23) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_29) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (8_5) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (18_27) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_12) 	<m_str>Mr. Hebborn</m_str> (8_7) 	<m_str>Mr. Hebborn</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Hebborn 's forging</m_str> (20_1) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (12_10) 	<m_str>Hebborn 's</m_str> (20_2) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_14) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_17) 	<m_str>Mr. Hebborn</m_str> (5_8) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (18_